r time that the church\nfk i as running the party in the State, but\nl'uU 3 -cy did not believe it, and now that\nfea' $fimircM COIlt,ol of a newapapor iu tho\nm .capital city of the Stato has been ac\nWfji cured their eyes arc opened and they\nt begin lo realize what church domination\nweans.\nThat James H. Brady engiueorcd tho\ndeal is the belief of 'many, and they\nare incensed at his action'. Republicans\nwho believe in the principles of Rcpub\nrtifrlcat\"sm now sce w3' tne apportion\nin fmcnt of delegates to the State couven\nMf was made as it -wag.\nMormon Counties Solid.\nfj The Mormon counties always vole\nteolid in convention, the delegates from\noff 'those, counties have always been couu\nhf? eled and they always obc3', otherwise\nff' -excommunication stares thorn in the\nface. Republicans hero now' see the\n'm tentacles of tho Mormon octopus twin\nit around them, and desperate effort\n.aft ;will be mado. fo break the hold. Of\nppursR, the Brady crowd here will man\ninnlate the Ada county delegation to\nIU 'l10 State, conventions. This county- has\nii twenty-four delegates, but nine more\nire necessary to conu'oi, ana Lnese can\nrtt Qnlv be secured from BJaiue, Canyon\nCnn Elmore counties, which have tlnrtv\n&St l'0tC3-\njcj-s. IThis done, Brady has a strangle hold\n3 upon tho party, the 'rank and file will\nbe expected to dance to the music he\nA aiitl his Mormon constituency- will plaj'.\njfc Revolt In the North.\n'fa But the middle and northern part of\nthe Stnte, which has long been on the\njjj.il :ve of an open rebellion, is now likely\nbreak loose and revolt against tho\nWS3 whom the lecherous and law-brcak-jjii\nng hierarchy in Salt Lake has selected\nJji A i manage affairs political in tho State'.\njH Phc people, that is the voters, have had\na ta) rongh this last action of tho church\nhsJ !r8Vclalion which has not been promul\n'et or niae known to them bv the\nr tif ogtis prophet, the law-defying seer, the\nAili ichorous and besiial revulator who has\nT loe mlcd Utah and who hopes to\nfl nlarge his kingdom by taking in the\n5l' :emfeti\nU3RYAN IS GUARDED IN\n1 CRITICISING ROOSEVELT,\ntOKCOLUytBUS. 0 Feb. IS. William .T.\niorf'1S?n' ln an interview here today, said.\nTtaBM tjt say just how mucli President\nvmoosevelta attitude- has had to do with\nlWS tcent Hnanclal disturbance. If his\ne i'y \"Kationa or recommondatlons have\nto aguocKo the water out of\nWMBtfTra \"tock the blame should fall not\niitKf \"!n on thoso who havo watered\n'fc'm? am M-\" cr'tlclsm would be that\nJH 2!rt4.not commcncG soon enough to\nBSm- iho fort' 'i'he sreat cjuoations to\nlc attention in the coming: cam\nJ\"!2KrJ; .bel.icvc'\" sald Mr. liryan. \"are\nUifJK.fL81, lhe tarIrr- and these railroad\nI n,5' BHt ono ,ESU runs through\n''rsmKi I ,0t llowcver, and that is. shall\n,itlBf ver\"me\"t toe admlnlstored in be-\nrf&m-ii ,U,.C, Pcn'e or for the bcnellt\nfew of the people?\"\nla W'NJCIPAL ELECTIONS IN\njgK- QUAKER STATE QUIET\nOtBinW1' Pob- With the\nw of nv. war(Jn whicii thero\nanv ,r,y.affftr. and passed off with\niK'jKf,\"\"10\"! incidents.\nfcirial. 01 the ward contests was the\nV 1Wfr6l!ft .i!ragod 'y wc Ulster, the\n.iiiR was a CIty party candidate\nlS warndClh),En ,,n tl10 Seventh ward\nflS6rflv r na-' always returned largo\n-ers MriSw?,ru,lheI,K,,-PUbIIcari candidates.\nt mR &lth'MHnS the energetic ca.w\n-t,HW hv a y uthe n,ovelist Scgcr was.\n4'liere todaJ Lh TConCTe?nlonal district\nlfc arid ,an'1 named Lawrence 1.\niR- wcro i,,rM ,atJonal convention.\niWdley il''tl11cJel \"r Taft. Herbert\ntJMF y aa endoraed for Governor.\nW 4\nSTORM KING RULES\nII MILE WEST\ni\nCountry from Luke to Missouri\nRiver Valley in blizzard's\nGrasp.\nCHICAGO PARTICULARLY\nIS SEVERE SUFFERER\nI\nTraffic Impeded by Drifting\nSnow. Owing to Extremo Ve\nlocity of Wind.\nCHICAGO, Tob. 18 The most vio\nlent storm that has visited Chicago in\nmany years commenced at 7 o'clock\nthis morning, and tonight in raging with\nincreasing violence, with no prospect of\na lessening of its violence before morn\nI in- s\nBy 4 o'clock in the afternoon Foven\ninches of snow had fallen, and it was\nstil coming down heavily. The wind\nat frequent intervals blew with a veloc\nity of fiftj' miles an hour, and it\nhurled the. snow through the streets\nin such blinding clouds that it was im\npossible to see for a greater distance\nthan .a half square, and often tho range\nof vision would be limited to a few\nfeet. A great number of accidents of\na minor character were caused by col\nlisions between wagons and streetcars.\nLip to G o'clock tonight no serious ac\ncident had been reported, although a\nnumber of people had been injured by\nwagons aud by falls on the pavements.\nDanger at Crossings.\nAt 5 o'clock, when the home-going\ncrowd was thickest, the wind was blow\ning so heavily and the snow was falling\nin such blinding sheets that it was posi\ntively dangerous to attempt to cross\nMichigan avenue aud its intersection -with\ncither Jack-Arm hnulnwirsi v..,,\nBuren streets. These crossings are used\nby thousands of people overy night to\nreach their homes in the southern part\nli a\"fl m thc suburbs by means\nof the Illinois Central railroad. Tt was\nrouud necessary to station a large unm\nber of city and park police at; thepo\ncorners to assist woman, and often it\nwas more than one officer could do to\npilot a woman across without assist\nance. It was out of the question for a\nwoman to cross the street bv herself.\nAn officer was stationed a half square\nwest of tho crossing of Jackson boule\nvard and Michigan aVenuc, with orders\nto send women back or to bring them\nthrough the Strndford hotel, bv which\nmeans the worst portion of the \"crosainir\nwas evaded.\nThe streetcar companies and tho ele\nvated roads fared well throughout the\ndny, but the heavy increase of snow\nthat came in the late afternoon made\ndesperate work for them. Every avail\nable man and all thc snow plows were\nconstantly at. vrork. in keeping tho tracks\nclear. In the suburbs the trolley lines\nwere operated with great difficulty be\ncause of tho Konstantlv increasing\ndrifts, and locomotiou became constant\nly .more .difficult. It was estimated at\nthe weather bureau that tho fall of\nsnow would amount to one foot or more\nby morning.\nTRAINS DELAYED BY\nDRIFTING .OF THE SNOW\nOMATIA, Neb.. T'eb. 18. Following\na continuous fall. of snow lasting twenty-four\nhours, accompanied by a wind\nwhich heaped it into drifts and almost\ntied up all kinds of street traffic, the\nmercury began a downward course this\nevening. All railroad trains were late\nand.- in sompv instances, morning over\nland trains did not reach Omaha until\nthi's.ieveuing.\nNearly Id inches of snow fell, tho\nheaviest in twenty years. There was\na heavy ruu of live stock at the varda\ntoday, and rnnch suffering from\" the\n8torm was tho result. Several stock\ntrains which have boon on the road\nsince yesterday have not reached the\nyard. Live stock, is being hastily un\nloaded as it arrives tonight and rushed\nto feeding pens.\nHEAVY\" SNOWFALL OVER\nPORTIONS OF KANSAS\nKANSAS CITY. Feb. 18. Thc snow\nstorm that prevailed all day in Kansas\nand western Missouri continues tonight,\nbut without low temperature, most\npoints reporting thc thermometer above\n20 degrees. In Kansas City tho suow\nfall tip to 9 o'clock tonight was about;\ninches, but in southern and central\nKansas 4 or 5 inches has fallen. Trains\nare not seriously delayed, and the\nstorm is highly satisfactory to wheat\ngrowers and fruit men.\nSHOT AND KILLED IN\nQUARREL WITH TENANT\nOKLAHOMA CITY, Okla., Feb. IS.\nZ. E. Becmblossom was shot and\nkilled at noon today on his farm, three\nmiles north of this city, by J. C. Wood\nson, a former tenant, with whom he\nbecame involved in a quarrel. Mr.\nBeamblossom w.13 a. former \"policeman\nof this city and later United States\nMarshal and United States cattle in\nspector, and took a prominent part iu\ncounty and State politics.\nMr. Woodson claims he shot in solf\ndefense. Bo came to town and sur\nrendered to the Sheriff at once.\nMayor WantB a Rest-.\nLOXO BEACH. Oil., Feb. IS. Robnrt\nA. Smith, the octogenarian flJavor of St.\nPaul, Minn., whose departure from IiIh\nhome upon tho eve of the primary elec\ntlon wlilch will decide his suc'ccksot.\ncaused considerable speculation, has bocu\nfor several days a guost at u, family\nhotel ln this city, where he propones re\nmaining until about May 1.\nMore Dolegates for Taft.\nSEDATjTA. Mo.. Feb. 1S. Republicans\nof tho Seventh Congressional district, ln\nconvention hero todny, elected dolegatCH\nto the Republican national convention at\nCblcavo, and instructed tlicm for Taft.\n\"NEVER TO UCHED ME.\n\"-J Food's'\nI 1\nPENNYPAGKER HUD\nIII THE GRAFT CASES\nDeclares Precautions Were\nTaken to Protect the Statt,\nbut Unsuspects Ignorance.\ni\nTrABRTSBUUG, T?a.J. JTeb. 15. For\nmer Gov. Pcnnypackcr was an import\nant witness nt tho State capitol con\nspiracy trial toda3'. Mr. Pcnnypackcr,\nby virtue of his office as Governor, was\npresident of the Board of Grounds and\nBuildings during the equipment of the\ncapitol. His colleagues on thc board\nwere former Auditor-General Snyder\nand former State Treasurer Mathues.\nIts active officer was former Superin\ntendent Shumaker.\nThc former Governor was called as\na witness for these three former State\nofficers.\nMr. Pennypacker said extraordinarv\nprecautions had been taken to safe\nguard tho commonwealth in the pay\nment of bills, by requiring tho archi.\ntect and thc superintendent of grounds\nand buildings to ee.rt.ifv to them, and\nthe contractor to take oath to their\ncorrectness.\nIgnorant of Payments.\nThe former Governor admitted under\ncross-examination that ho did not know\nthat $1,009,000 had been paid by Sny\nder and Mathues tq Sanderson without\nthe approval of tho board, or that on\nJanuary 10, 1D05. tho date of tho adop\ntion of the resolution by the board re\nquiring tho architect's certificate on\nbills, $2,000,000 had been paid to San\nderson in excess of Hueston's estimate\non tho cost of the furnishings.\nMr. Pennypacker said he had no rea\nson lor thinking that Ilueston did not\ndo as fnlly as he could the work he\nwas called upon to do. \"If von are\nasking mo for a judgment,\" he said,\nJ think it is a groat achievement.\"\nAsked how long his reliance upon the\narchitect continued, his answer was:\nIt continues down to tho presout\ntime, until I am shown reason to tho\ncontrary.\"\nJust Lumped the \"Feot.\"\nThe commonwealth showed in tho\ncross-examination of James II. Steven\nson, Sanderson's bookkeeper, that bills\nfor furniture for the Senate and House\namounting to over $600,000 were made\nout as sq many feet in bulk and paid\nin tho course of Sanderson's business,\nand that, sovcral months afterward Ste\nvenson, when ordered by Sanderson to\nmake out detailed bills, simply took\nthe lump sum of feet and appor\ntioned' it among the articles, glean\ning some information from blueprints,\nand receiving tho remainder from San\nderson. Stevenson had some \"feet\" left, and\nhe added that to tho rostrums of the\nMcnato and House caucus rooms. Evi\ndence was introduced by the defense\nto show that in spite ofkhe \"approxi\nmation\" system of billing the Sander\nson furnishings, the Stato was thc\ngainer to the extent of S34S.227 on\nSanderson's bills for furniture and\nthnt SanderBon could have collected l\n224,292 iustcad of $876,066 for the\nfurniture.\nProvo News Items.\nSpecial lo The Tribune.\nPROVO. Feb. 18. C. West, the m-n\nwho left Osrden with tho Intention of\ncoming to Provo to kill somo of thQ asv\nlum attendants, has been apprehended n\nEureka, and tho Oeden officers have been\nnotified. cn\nClarence Dangorfield and Georre w\nman were lined 310 each today irT tho\nPolice court, for setting drumj on Sun\nday latit.\nLicenses to wed have been Insucd (n\nJohn Hansen of Richfield and Mine l\"\nHanucn of Provo: Fred Jackman Jf Sa\nlem and Ada Kendrld of Sprlngvillc\nEighteen laboring men were provided\nwith mcaln and a night'.-? lodeln- at the\nI clly and county Jails here, lawt night,\no\n\"PRESIDENT Mil\"\nSLOGAN OF 11L1I1S\nRepublican State Central Com\nmittee Gives Veteran Speak\ner of House Support.\nSPRINGFIELD, TIL, Fob. IS. The\nTopublican Stato central committee\nmet this morning and adopted resolu\ntions indorsing Joseph G. Cannon for\nthc Presidency, and fixed March 26 as\nthc dato for holding tho State conven\ntion in this city.\nTho resolutions adopted by the Stato\ncentral committee, after indorsing the\npolicy of President Eooscvelt \"in ad\nministrating oven-handed justice to all\ntho people of the United States, with\nout regard to persons, and in thc char\nacter of his recommendations to thc\nCongress,\" proceeded as follows:\nAppeal for Support.\n\"We invito the attention of tho\ncountry to the well-known fact that\nwithout, thc cordial, earnest and con\nstant spirit of the lion. Joseph G. Can\nnon, ns Speaker of the House of .Repre\nsentatives, it would have been impossi\nble for tho rocommeiidat ious or the\nPresident to have been enacted into\nlaw, aud that tho policy of the Repub\nlican party, as manifested 13' thc Presi\ndent and enacted by the Congress,\ncannot bo better carried out and con\ntinued than by placing thc administra\ntion of the same in the hands of thc\nman whoso authority and influence\nhas been second only to that, of Presi\ndent Roosevelt himself.\"\nTho resolutions close with formal in\ndorsement of Speaker Cannon for\nPresident.\nPresident McMurray, Alderman \"Fow\nJor and other representatives of thc\nTaft club of Chicago appeared beforo\nthe. committee- to ask that provision bo\nmade for a primary volo on President.\nCol. George Buckingham of Danville,\nspeaking for Mr. Cannon, said that\ntwice within four 3'cars tho State con\nvention had declared Mr. Cnnnon the\nchoice of Illinois for President; that\n90 per cent of thc Republicans of the\nState arc for him. and that Mr. Cannon\nwould not hesitate Ui submit his claims\nto a. primary voto if that wcro prac\nticable. \"Mr. Cannon believes,\" said Col,\nBuckingham, \"that tho Republicans of\neach district should be left to select\ntheir delegates in their own wa-.\nKILLING RESULT OP\nQUARREL WITH COOK\nSAN FRANCISCO, Feb. 18. James\nGrossman, a foreman of tho Bench\nGorvo Park grading camp, and living\nat f5S31 Mission street, wns shot and\nkilled by Sam 'IVylor, the camp cook,\nat (3 o'clock thia morning, after. a quar\nrel over the preparation of eggs for\nthe foreman's breakfast. Taylor, now\nclaiming that he acted in self-defense,\nfired six shots at Grossman, all of which\ntook effect, four in the body, one in'\ntho arm and ono in tbo log. Policeman\nArcher was on the scone immediately,\nplaced Taylor under arrest, and had\nGrossmau sent to f.he hospital. The\nlatter died before tho doctors could do\nanything for him.\nONLY THREE KILLED IN\nPOWDER MILL EXPLOSION\nWHARTON\". K. B., Fob, IS.-An' ex\nplosion in the mixing- department of the\nGoneral Explosive company in this vil\nlage today killed three employees Joseph\nHough, Dovld Utter and James Kevcrn,\nand broke nearly every window In utorcs\nand residences In Wharton nnd some\nwindow a in Dover, two miles distant.\nt\nLARGE DECREASE II\nJAP IMM1GRATI0H\nSecretary Straus Submits Signi\nficant Figures to President\nat Meeting of Cabinet.\ni\nWASHINGTON, Feb. IS. At the\nCabinet meeting today. Secretary\nStraus of tho Department of Commerce\nand Labor laid before the President\nsome significant figures as to iniinigrr\ntiou and emigration. The figures show\nthat for January thero was a large\ndecrease in tho number of Japanese\narriving in tho United States. Thc\ntotal arrivals for both the mainland\nand Hawaii were 971, as compared with\nabout 5000 for January, 1907, Mr.\nStraus did not. offer any explanation\nas to tho falling off in\" Japanese nr-\nri-n le\nAs to the immigration to the Uuitod\nStates from other countries, Mr. Straus\npaid tho total for Januarv was, in round\nnumbers, 2700, as compared with 5400\nin January one year ago, a decrease\nof 50 per cent. Mr. Straus showed\nthnt fcr the months of July, August,\nSeptember and October the totnl im\nmigration to the United States was\n4G.',000, while tho emigration for tho\nsame period was 190,000. Tho figures\non emigration for November, Decem\nber, January aud February, not yet\nprepared, a;re expected to show a still\ngreater ratio as compared lo immigra\ntion, there hnving been a largo outgo\nof foreigners in November nnd De-combor.\nALABAMA IN LINE WITH\nROOSEVELT AND TAFT\nBIRMINGHAM, Ala., Feb. IS. Tho\nStato Republican executive committee\ntodny passed a resolution endorsing the\nadministration of President Roosevelt\nand thc candidacy of Secretary Taft\nfor president. Thc resolution was\" adopt\ned by a vote of '.10 to 2.\nWhen the committee met, Chairman\nJ.4 M. Thompson presiding, thirty of\nihirly-iwo members were present.\nChairman Thompson advocated harmony\nand a united party. A motion was pre\nsented that all members tha had affili\nated with thc Davidson party in a re\ncent mcctiug be expelled from tho com\nmittee, headed by Chairman Thomp\nson. W. F. Aldrich, former Congress\nman, who has a bruised eye, the result\nof a blow given last night at tho hotel\nby Chairman Thompson, questioned the\nright of thc committee to expel 3113'\nmembers, aud said that he thought the\nDavidson committee was the rightful\none. Tho motion to expel Davidson,\nhowever, prevailed.\nI\nAmerican Fork Nows.\nSpecial to The Tribune.\nAMERICAN FORK, Feb. IS- Thomas\nSmith. Jr., or this city, has Just re\nturned home from tho r.atlor-dav Saints'\nhospital, whero he underwent an opera\ntion for appendicitis. After this was per\nformed he was compelled to undergo an\nother for the romoval of his right kid\nney, lie has recovered very nlcelv.\nThe Utah County Light nnd 'Power\ncompany today commenced work on thc\nPower line from thin city to Knights\nvillo, for the lCnlght smelter. L.prgc\nforces of men wer put to work digging\nthe pole holes, and preparing the poles\nfor erection. Thc work win bo dono from\nthis end of thc line toward the smelter\nTho compuny expecta that it will re\nquire about seventy-live days to completo\nthe line work. Tho two transformer sta\ntions which will be erected will coat\n510,000 each.\nBig Grain Dealers Fall.\nBOSTON, Fob. IS. J. D. Cresaey\nGo gTaln dealers, made an assignment\ntoday. Inability to realize on customers'\nnotco is given ns tho cause. The liabili\nties are given as $125,000 and thc asets\na 10 wild to be large.\n.j\nRAILWAY PAYS IS.\nSnUKSIiJ1S.W\nFive Years of Litigation Brings\nWoman Big Sum for Hus\nband's Death.\nFIGHT IN COURTS ENDS\nAFTER ACTIONS ON APPEAL\nVictim Was Run Down in 1902\nby Car. Making Flying c\nSwitch.\nAfter more than five years of litiga\ntion, during which throe trials have\nbeen had aud one appeal taken to thc\nSupreme Court, the $00,000 damage\nsuit of Emeliue Spiking against the\nUtah Light and Railway company is a\nclosed incident. The close came Tues\nday, when a representative of the Utah\nLight and Railway company handed\nCounty Clerk Eldredgc a draft for $16,\n815.48, which he, in turn, will hand to\nPowers Marioneaux, attorneys for\nMrs. bp iking.\nTho basis of the suit was the killing\nol Ihomas W. Spiking, husband of\nMrs. Spiking, by a street car on Second\nbouth street, just east of Main street,\non the evening of August; .10, 1902. A\nflying switch wa being made by thc\ncar at the time .it struck Spiking and\nthe lights wero out. Spiking was cross\ning thc track and dirl not realize his\ndanger, because of thc absence of the\nlights.\nUpon tho first trial of tho case tho\n,iury disagreed. On the second trial\na verdict was rendered in favor of the\nplaintiff for $25,000, but the court\ngranted a new trial. Upon thc third\nhearing n verdict was returned for\n$15,000 and an appeal was taken bv\ntlit; company to tho Supreme. 'Court,\nvnerc tnc judgment was recently af\nfirmed. The .'?1G.815.4S paid Tuesdav\nrepresented the original judgment o\"f\n1 5.000, with accrued interest.\nThis is thc largest judgment in a\npersonal injury case ever paid in Salt\nLake county.\nDISTRICT COURT IN\nSESSION AT COALVILLE\nSpecial to Thc Tribune.\nCOALVTLL.E, Feb. 18. A session of the\ndistrict court was held here todav. Judge\nMorris L. Rlchlo presiding, and 'the fol\nlowing business woh transacted:\nGuardianship of Chcmlsch P. Sndcrup,\nct al., minors: account of guardian ap\nproved.\nGuardianship of Sophia. Mav Steele, ct\nal, minors; petition for letters of guard\nianship and removal of guardian hereto\nfore appointed, continued to March 1C.\nGuardianship of William Reeves, ct nl.,\nminors; return of sale of real estate ap\nproved. Estate of John Larson, deceased; final\naccount of executor approved; distribu\ntion of estate continued to March .16.\nEstate of George II. Reynolds, deceased;\nfinal account of executor approved and\ndistribution of estato made to two minor\nchlldron of deceased, consisting of per\nsonal property to the amount of about\n$6000.\nEstate of William II. Kimball, deceased;\nwill admitted to, probate; C. B. Stewart\nappumicu executor, and his bond fixed\nat $15,000.\nEstate of Ellen DeHufi, deceased; will\nadmitted to probate; Thomas Galligan ap\npointed executor to act without bond.\nJess F, Drake of Park City was granted\na decree of divorce from Clarence Drake\non the grounds of rallnrc to provide the\nnecessities of life.\nGuardianship of Thelma and Clarence\nMead Reynolds, minors; Mrs. Mulvina\nReynolds was app.olnted .guardian of the\npersons of snld minors, and Dr. T. A.\nDanncnbcrg was appointed guardian of\nthe estate of the minors. The bond of tho\nformer was llxed at S00. and that of the\nlatter at 511.400.\nNellie McGlvern. plaintiff, vs. .Thomas\nmotion to set nsldo default in this easo\nwas argued by counsel and taken under\nadvisement .by the court.\nState of Utuh. ex-re!., Coalville Co-op.,\nvs. Alma Eldrcdire. writ of mandate rnn. I\ntlnued to March 1G.\nAn order was made for thirty jurors,\ni returnable on March Jt5, at 2 p. m.\nAll Jury cases at Issue In tho court wcro\nset for trial on March 16. and all non\njury cases on tho 17th Inst. There will\nbe about seven Jury cases.\nTho following attorneys were here to\nattend court; L. B. Wight. Henry Shields.\nPark City; B. J. Stewart. C. II. Jack.\nDan B. Shields, Frank Evans, Salt Lake\nCity.\nMrs. C. W. Hodgson of Park City was\nhere as a witness In a case before thc\ncourt Monday.\nManager S. 13. Whitley of the Park\nCity Bell Telephone exchange, was here\non business Monday.\nCounty Surveyor R. A. Jones, and John\nC. Paskett of Ilenefer, wore hero on\nbusiness today.\nAFTER THE SPRING VILLE\nLIQUOR DEALERS\nSpecial to Tho Tribune.\nSPRING VILLE, Fob. IS. lohn R. Men\ncrny, a clerk in C. E. Tranchell's drug\nstore here, who was found gulltv yes\nterday In the jus! Ice court of selling in\ntoxicating liquor In violation of tho city\nordinance, was today sentencod by Jus\ntice Jas, E. Hall to a fine of $200, six\nmonths' imprisonment in tho countv Jail.\nThis is the second case of this kind un\nder the new administration. Wm. Curtis\nwas tried a few days ago and found\nguilty of the same ofrensc and was given\nthirty days' imprisonment in the countv\nJail. He Is now serving out his sentonce.\nMr. Mcneray will appeal his case to tho\ndistrict court. Wm. Curtis, mentioned\nabove as serving time for sclllug liquor\nin violation of a city ordinance, was one I\nof the witnesses against Menerny\nWILL CHANGE DEFUNCT BANK\"\nTO NATIONAL DEPOSITORY j\nSpecial to The Tribune.\nBOISE, Feb. IS. A move is now on\nfoot, to reorganize the Capital Stato bank,\nthe new institution to be called Tho Cap\nital National Bank of Idaho, and appli\ncation has boon made to the Comptroller\nof the Currency to authorize Its estab\nlishment. It Is planned to organise with\na capital of 5350,000 and thc new bank will\ntake over tho 'business of the defunct\nCapital otato bank. It is hoped to open\nsoon and the depositors of the Capital\nStato will be paid in full.\ni\nt\nSTOKE DISCUSSES 1\nFINANCIAL PANIC 1\nRegards the Aldrich Bill as J9\nMerely Makeshift in Meet- 9\ning Country's Needs. M\nOPPOSES MORE POWER\" -J\nFOR THE NATIONAL BANKS' 1\ni f\nFavors La.w Demanding that Re- 1 1\nserves Be Kept in the Conn-\ntry's Banks.\n\nWASHINGTON, Feb. 13. Speaking\nin the Senate today, Mr. Stone of Mis\nsouri declared that while the recent Ir'ifl\nfinancial panic was in part due lo :i .'Tjf\nshortage of available currency, the con-\neentration of thc money t given points 1\nhad much to do with it. There wa3, \"J\nhe said, too much of this money' in\nNew York. The Aldrich bill ho regard-\ncd as merely a makeshift in meeting ,8jf\nthe needs of the country.\n\"Z am opposed,\" he said, \"to con- V M\nJernng this great additional favor and 'f?2B\npower upon national banks. Thy idea, ffU\not a corporation usurping and usinp- rjH\nthe funds of a nalidn has always been Sll\nobnoxious to me. Tim power tiirv can J 41\nexercise upon tho political and indn8- .19\ntrial well-being of the Nation is enor- 9\nmous, and although it ia ji'o doubt, en- lifiM\ntirely true that the national banker is WxM\nas patriotic as tho average citizen, vet ft-SB\nmoney and business with him, as w'ith lv3M\nothers, arc generally selfish and grasp- IpM\ning things, and dividends are often TlB\nregarded as of more importance than R m\npatriotism.\" flM\nObjocts to Giving Bank Power. Iff\nlie objected to giving the bank H'fM\npower .to. regulate in any degree thc tf.'M\ntuimuu ui. me peopic-s currency by H\nexpanding or contracting it, as\" mav KitH\nhappen to suit their whims or thir KaH\ninterests. fjrfl\nMr. Stone declared that he would IWM\nprefer to curtail .tho powers of tho Vm\nbanks because the Government is now Pffl\ndepended upon to five stahilit.v fn tbo\ncurrency. &fl\n'